The effect of tighter preselection cuts on the cross section limit was evaluated by setting tighter cuts and calculating the new limit. Table \ref{cut_limit} show the several variations made. 

\begin{table}[h!]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|}\hline
Variable name                   & Variation                & Limit (r) \\ \hline\hline
Loose cuts                      & see table (include ref)  & $<2.92887$\\\hline
nBJetLoose25                    & $\geq 1 \to \geq 2$      & $<3.8057$\\\hline
nBJetMedium25$\geq 1$           & Loose to Medium tag Bjet & $<2.7559$\\\hline
MaxEtaJet25                     & $\geq 0 \to \geq 1$      & $<2.9385$\\\hline
MaxEtaJet25                     & $\geq 0 \to \geq 1.5$    & $<2.9990$\\\hline
met_pT$> 30$                    & add MET cut              & $<2.9053$\\\hline
Zveto                           & $>10 \to > 15$           & $<2.7881$\\\hline
nBJetMedium25$\geq 1$ + Zveto   & combined                 & $<2.6162$\\\hline
\end{tabular}
\caption{Limit variation as a function of tighter cuts}
\label{cut_limit}
\end{table}





the cross section limit can change as a function of the bin size in the signal/bg mva1vs mva2 2D plot. Several sizes and binning combination were tested in order to optimize the limit as shown in figure \ref{bins}, turning the 2d histogram of mva1 vs mva2 into a 1d histogram for shape fitting in combine. Among the combinations, the best limit was found for 10 bins.

\begin{figure} [!h]
 \centering
 \includegraphics[width=4cm ,height=4cm]{figures/bin_scheeme.pdf} 
\caption{Binning combination scheme.}
\label{input_var}
\end{figure}


the limits of the bins are at:

default: x_1=-0.5 ; x_2=0.0 ; x_3=0.5 ; y_1=-0.5 ; y_2=0.0 ; y_3=0.5
cross section limit: r<2.9287

optimized: x_1=-0.5 ; x_2=0.4 ; x_3=0.7 ; y_1=-0.5 ; y_2=0.4 ; y_3=0.7
cross section limit: r<2.8105




if we additionally consider the optimization using tighter pre-selection cuts (see pre-section studies)

we get as optimized limit: r<2.5938





